@node purpose "Purpose"

	Purpose of this player:
	-----------------------

	  Why was this program written. You can see immediately that it	can't
	compete with the current replayer programs that are available as free
	ware. This program has been more like a test tool for me when I've
	been writing the libraries that do the actual replaying. There was no
	need to write a massive player, just a simple program that is small
	and fast. The whole program is written in 100% assembly language, so
	I think I've reached my goal.

	  If this player is not good, then why it was released?? Well, I
	thought that when I finally release the library collection into
	public, I thougt it would be cool to make two packages. One is USER
	package (this is it) and the other is DEVELOPER package. Besides
	some of you might like this tiny replayer. Check out the @{" Usage " link howtouse }

@endnode

@node requirements "Requirements"

	System requirements:
	--------------------

	  The only piece of software that is absolutely required to run
	BFBPlayer is:

	@{" reqtools.library " link thanks } (any version will do)

	  And if you want to play MED/OctaMED or PlaySID modules, or perhaps
	use the xpkdecrunch option, you need following in order these libs to
	use the features:

	medplayer.library v2+
	playsid.library   v1+
	xpkmaster.library v2+

	  The only needed hardware is 020+ for THX sound system library. You
	are not able to play the THX tunes without one.

	  Note that there exist two versions of BFBPlayer. One for KickStart
	v1.3+ and one for KickStart v2.04+ which relys completely on the
	KS2.04+ features. Feel free to choose the right program to suit your
	needs.

@endnode

@node notes "Notes about the replayers"

	@{b}Notes about the replayers:@{ub}
	--------------------------

	Some small notes about specific replay libraries. Some libs are not
	mentioned here, but that's because they don't have anything to note.

	- @{b}MED / OctaMED		(bfbplayMED!.library)@{ub}
	  The library uses medplayer.library v2 to playback the modules,
	  so make sure that it exist in your LIBS: path. And make sure it's
	  the version 2!!

	- @{b}The Player 6.0a	(bfbplayP60A.library)@{ub}
	  When the module is started, there happens few enforcer hits but
	  then they are gone. I know where the hits are coming from but I
	  don't know why. I'm trying to fix. These hits are not dangerous.

	- @{b}PlaySID		(bfbplayPSID.library)@{ub}
	  bfbplayPSID.library uses playsib.library 1.1 to play the PSID
	  tunes. Make sure it exists in your LIBS: path. Due to a bug in
	  the playsid.library it doesn't work with the KickStart 1.3. That's
	  why the player checks if you're running it on KS1.3 and prevents
	  you from playing the PSID tunes if yes.

	- @{b}ProTracker		(bfbplayPT20.library)@{ub}
	  Used replaycode is from ProTracker 2.2, but although it has been
	  almost completely rewritten, I don't know anything about the
	  possible ProTracker 3.0+ specific commands. So, if there exists any,
	  this replayer most likely isn't capable to play them.

	- @{b}THX sound system	(bfbplayTHXS.library)@{ub}
	  Needs 020+ CPU to play the tunes. The library checks for the CPU,
	  so you cannot start playback if you don't have 020+ CPU. And
	  during the test only one module caused enforcer hits. I dunno
	  if this is a serious problem.
@endnode

@node howtouse "How to use"

	How to use:
	-----------

	  I think everything is clear if I explain the GUI.

	+------------------------------------------+
	|@{"  BFBPlayer v1.1 (c) 1996 BFB Team  " link but1 } @{" o " link but2 }|
	|------------------------------------------|
	|@{"  |<   " link but3 }@{"   >|  " link but4 }Type:@{"ProTracker          " link but5 }|
	|@{" P " link but6 }@{" > " link but7 }@{" S " libk but20}@{" D " link but8 }Name:@{"Rave-storm IV       " link but9 }|
	|@{"  <<   " link but10 }@{"   >>  " link but11 } Pos:@{" 20" link but12 }/@{" 56" link but13} Mod:@{" 2" link but14 }/@{" 5" link but15 }|
	+------------------------------------------+

@endnode

@node but1 "About button"

	This is the about button. By pressing it you can see the author
	information.

@endnode

@node but2 "Animation button"

	This gadget is just making you happy. :) As you can see, when the
	animation is running, the BFBPlayer is in a small busyloop. By
	pressing this gadget, you can toggle the flag that tells if the man
	should be animated or not.

@endnode

@node but3 "Previous module"

	If module has several modules inside it, you can jump to previous
	module with this button. 

@endnode

@node but4 "Next module"

	If module has several modules inside it, you can jump to next
	module with this button. 

@endnode

@node but5 "Author information"

	On this gadget you can see the current format of a module that is
	playing. If you press the gadget, you see the author of the
	replayer.

@endnode

@node but6 "Pause module"

	This buttons pauses the current module playback. Note that not
	all modules can be paused. IF not, then this button has no effect.

@endnode

@node but7 "Play module"

	This button starts the playback. If pressed for the first time,
	the channels are allocated and the interrupts are reset. If
	you press this gdget when the module is already playing, the
	module restarts from beginning.

@endnode

@node but20 "Stop module"

	This gadget stops the module play. Note that is you press the
	gadget when a module is not playing, the module will be ejected.
	During the eject, channels are released and interrupts are given
	away.

@endnode

@node but8 "Disk Operation"

	This open a file requester to allow you to choose a module file.

@endnode

@node but9 "Sample texts"

	On this gadget you can see the real module name, or if the module
	doesn't have one, then the filename but without suffixes. By pressing
	this gadget you can see the sampletexts.

@endnode

@node but10 "Previous pattern"

	If one can jump between patterns inside a module, then this gadget
	jump one back.

@endnode

@node but11 "Next pattern"

	If one can jump between patterns inside a module, then this gadget
	jump one forward.

@endnode

@node but12 "Current pattern"

	This on tells you the current pattern number, if it can be
	calculated. This and the maxpatterns field remain zero if the
	pattern number cannot be read.

@endnode

@node but13 "Max patterns"

	This on tells you the max pattern number, if it can be calculated.
	This and the current pattern field remains zero if the pattern
	number cannot be read.

@endnode

@node but14 "Current subsong"

	This on tells you the current subsong number, if it can be
	calculated.

@endnode

@node but15 "Max subsongs"

	This one tells you the total subsongs in this module if it can
	be calculated.

@endnode

