@node prefs "Preferences setup"

	Preferences setup
	-----------------

	Actually there is no separate preferences window from where you could
	set your own prefs to make the program to suit your needs. Well,
	how the prefs should be then saved if there's not even a save gadget
	to do that action.

	Just activate the window and press letter 's' to save setup. BFBPlayer
	will inform you if the prefs were saved succesfully, but if nothing
	comes up, something has gone wrong. This might have caused by two
	possible reasons.

	 1) You've ran out of memory. Yes, saving the prefs needs 150 bytes
	    of extra memory.
	 2) The prefs file couldn't be opened. The name of the prefs file
	    is 'S:BFBPlayer.prefs'. Make sure the bfbplayer can save with that
	    name.

	If the prefs were saved, a message like: "Preferences saved
	succesfully!" will occure. What is saved then?

	 1) The location of the main window. Next time you boot, the window
	    will appear there.
	 2) The location of the sample texts window. When you move a sample
	    txts window, the BFBPlayer tracks the movement all the time and
	    the location is then saved into this file too. When you next time
	    open the sample texts window, it will appear there, where you
	    closed it last.
	 3) Your module path. The modulepath is read from the reqtools
	    requester, so by selecting your module path, closing the
	    requester and then saving the prefs will ensure that after every
	    boot, BFBPlayer opens its filerequester in this directory.

	Ok, sounds fair enough. Is there something it doesn't save?

	 1) Well, the only important thing in my opinnion is the zoom window
	    location. I don't know the way to read the zoomed window's
	    location so in every bootup, this location is set to the same
	    than the main window's location. In other words: if you zoom
	    the window after a boot, it zooms itself to the same location
	    where the main window just was located. However, this is only
	    a KS2.04+ feature!

	Well, can there be any problems? No, but if there still occures one,
	just delete the prefs, launch the program and save the prefs again.
	You just might have an old version of the prefs file.

@endnode
